This project uses machine learning techniques to identify and segment ionization cones in active galactic nuclei (AGN) using spatially-resolved [O III] emission maps.

## Background

Ionization cones are important signatures of AGN activity, often traced using [O III] lines. They can indicate the geometry of the narrow-line region and the extent of radiation escaping from the central engine.

This project is inspired by the need for automated methods in identifying these structures in large IFU dataset.

 IonizationCone-Automization
 Automatic Ionization Cone Detection in AGN via Imaging Data
 What Is This?

IonizationCone-Automization is a machine learning pipeline that automatically detects ionization cones in active galactic nuclei (AGN) using 2D emission-line imaging data, such as [O III] maps from JWST or HST.
It replaces manual, time-consuming segmentation with a trained UNet model — making analysis fast, repeatable, and scalable.
 Why It Matters

    “Imaging observation is more efficient with a large field of view, which means the method developed based on images will have wide applications.”
    — Mentor insight

Large-scale imaging surveys produce massive volumes of AGN data. Manual cone identification limits scientific throughput and introduces subjective bias. This tool automates that detection, enabling:

    Faster AGN classification

    Morphological studies across redshift

    Exploration of obscuration, orientation, and feedback

 What It Does

 Trains on 2D synthetic and real narrowband images
 Predicts binary ionization cone masks from FITS or .npy inputs
 Visualizes segmentation results and saves predictions
 Evaluates performance with IoU, Dice, Precision, Recall
 Designed for research reproducibility & modular extension
 Data In, Cone Out

    Input:

        2D [O III] (or similar) narrowband image (FITS or NumPy)

    Output:

        Binary mask predicting cone structure

        Optional visualization and metrics

        Model-ready .pth weights

Under the Hood

    Model: Custom 2D UNet architecture (src/models/model_2d.py)

    Loss: Weighted Dice + BCE

    Data Loader: Supports real and synthetic data (organized under data/)

    Training / Eval Scripts: Located in scripts/2d/

    Prediction: Drop your data in, run one script, and get segmentations

##  Objectives

- Create a reproducible pipeline to identify and segment ionization cones
- Train ML models on simulated or labeled AGN datasets
- Validate with known AGN cone geometries
- Generate valid model predictions

##  Project Structure

Ionization/
├── data/                   # Input data directory (FITS or .npy files)
│   └── sample.fits         # Example image file (or real observation)
│
├── results/                # Output data like masks, figures, and logs
│   └── example_mask.npy    # Example thresholded mask from preprocessing
│
├── scripts/                # Standalone scripts for running specific tasks
│   └── simulate.py         # Script to generate synthetic OIII cone images
│
├── src/
│   └── ionization/         # Source code for the core image processing tools
│       ├── __init__.py     # Initializes the ionization module
│       └── preprocess.py   # Functions for loading, normalizing, and thresholding images
│
├── venv/                   # Local Python virtual environment (not tracked by Git)
│   └── ...                 # Site-packages, binaries, etc.
│
├── .gitignore              # Ignores virtual environment, temp files, etc.
├── pyproject.toml          # Project metadata and dependencies (PEP 518)
├── README.md               # This documentation file

##  Setup

git clone https://github.com/yourusername/IonizationCone-Automization.git
cd IonizationCone-Automization
python3 -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate
pip install -r requirements.txt

